{"type":"message","id":"a37b77a1","parentId":"57260cb9","timestamp":"2026-03-14T03:57:20.652Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_c45db1482e1243648e023d82","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/memory/daily/2026-03-14.md","newText":"## 11:41 AM (Heartbeat)\n- Investigating OpenClaw PR status for session peer metadata\n- Our PR (eb591f29f) not merged — session files still lack peer info\n- Context Engine is different feature (routing, not storage)\n\n## 11:45 AM\n- Allan confirmed: Context Engine is about how context gets processed/constructed\n- Clarified difference: Context Engine = runtime routing, Our PR = persistent storage\n\n## 11:48 AM\n- Allan asked to check \"agent protocol\" feature\n- Found **ACP (Agent Communication Protocol)** in OpenClaw v2026.3.12\n- ACP is for running external coding agents (Codex, Claude Code, Gemini)\n- **ACP ≠ our PR** — doesn't solve peer metadata storage problem\n- Three different features now identified:\n  1. Context Engine — context routing decisions\n  2. ACP — external agent protocol\n  3. Our PR — peer metadata in session files (still not merged)\n\n## 11:56 AM (Heartbeat)\n- Researched ACP feature in OpenClaw\n- Confirmed ACP is for external agents, not peer metadata\n- Our PR still needed for chat extraction use case","oldText":"## 11:41 AM (Heartbeat)\n- Investigating OpenClaw PR status for session peer metadata\n- Our PR (eb591f29f) not merged — session files still lack peer info\n- Context Engine is different feature (routing, not storage)"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":84281,"output":356,"cacheRead":2752,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":87389,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773460607233}}
