{"type":"message","id":"1c892aca","parentId":"dda94ef6","timestamp":"2026-03-14T05:44:53.952Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_c711ad29f83a4e449c97a97e","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/memory/daily/2026-03-14.md","newText":"## 1:27 PM (Heartbeat)\n- Analyzed LCM schema vs our chat log system\n- LCM preserves messages but lacks peer metadata\n- Our PR still needed for participant identification\n\n## 1:38 PM\n- Allan asked if LCM is open source\n- Yes — MIT License by Josh Lehman / Martian Engineering\n- Can fork, modify, contribute back\n\n## 1:41 PM\n- Allan asked to compare our extract-chat tool with LCM\n- Both use SQLite, both read session JSONL files\n- Key differences:\n  - Our tool: Exports to MD, extracts peer info from message content, uses contacts.json\n  - LCM: DAG summarization, search tools, context management for LLM\n- **Same root problem**: Both lack peer metadata in session headers\n- Our tool works around it by parsing message content\n- LCM doesn't address it at all\n- Our PR (`eb591f29f`) would fix at source\n\n## 1:44 PM (Heartbeat)\n- Compared extract-chat.js with LCM\n- Both have same gap: no peer metadata in session headers\n- Our tool works around it, LCM doesn't address it","oldText":"## 1:27 PM (Heartbeat)\n- Analyzed LCM schema vs our chat log system\n- LCM preserves messages but lacks peer metadata\n- Our PR still needed for participant identification"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":82202,"output":331,"cacheRead":2752,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":85285,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773467052464}}
{"type":"message","id":"9d382c07","parentId":"1c892aca","timestamp":"2026-03-14T05:44:53.978Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_c711ad29f83a4e449c97a97e","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/memory/daily/2026-03-14.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 402 ## 1:27 PM (Heartbeat)\n 403 - Analyzed LCM schema vs our chat log system\n 404 - LCM preserves messages but lacks peer metadata\n 405 - Our PR still needed for participant identification\n+406 \n+407 ## 1:38 PM\n+408 - Allan asked if LCM is open source\n+409 - Yes — MIT License by Josh Lehman / Martian Engineering\n+410 - Can fork, modify, contribute back\n+411 \n+412 ## 1:41 PM\n+413 - Allan asked to compare our extract-chat tool with LCM\n+414 - Both use SQLite, both read session JSONL files\n+415 - Key differences:\n+416   - Our tool: Exports to MD, extracts peer info from message content, uses contacts.json\n+417   - LCM: DAG summarization, search tools, context management for LLM\n+418 - **Same root problem**: Both lack peer metadata in session headers\n+419 - Our tool works around it by parsing message content\n+420 - LCM doesn't address it at all\n+421 - Our PR (`eb591f29f`) would fix at source\n+422 \n+423 ## 1:44 PM (Heartbeat)\n+424 - Compared extract-chat.js with LCM\n+425 - Both have same gap: no peer metadata in session headers\n+426 - Our tool works around it, LCM doesn't address it\n 406 - **Context Gateway** (HN): External service for token compression before LLM\n 407 - Both relevant for clawish context management\n 408 \n 409 ### Pending Tasks\n     ...","firstChangedLine":406},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773467093966}}
