{"type":"message","id":"f425f62e","parentId":"18c20ee2","timestamp":"2026-03-14T13:10:33.222Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Good question! Let me compare:\n\n---\n\n## Option A: `year/month/date`\n\n```\nexports/\n├── dm/\n│   └── alice/\n│       └── 2026/\n│           └── 03/\n│               ├── 14.md\n│               └── 13.md\n```\n\n**Pros:**\n- Clear hierarchy\n- Easy to navigate by year, then month\n- Scales well for many years\n\n**Cons:**\n- Deeper nesting (4 levels)\n- More folders to click through\n\n---\n\n## Option B: `year-month/date` (current)\n\n```\nexports/\n├── dm/\n│   └── alice/\n│       └── 2026-03/\n│           ├── 2026-03-14.md\n│           └── 2026-03-13.md\n```\n\n**Pros:**\n- Shallower nesting (3 levels)\n- Folder name is self-explanatory (`2026-03`)\n- Matches our current structure\n\n**Cons:**\n- More folders at same level if many months\n\n---\n\n## My Recommendation: Keep `year-month/date`\n\nIt's what we already use, and it's simpler. The date in the filename (`2026-03-14.md`) is clear enough.\n\nWhat do you prefer?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":79885,"output":274,"cacheRead":2752,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":82911,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773493786758}}
